
  # Alert Generation System

This diagram shows how the alert system works in CHMS. The main idea of this subsystem is to monitor patient data and create alerts when values are not normal.

The AlertGenerator is the main class. It uses DataStorage to get patient data, which is shown as an association because it only reads the data and does not own it. I separated these two classes so that data storage and alert logic are independent. This makes the system easier to update or change later.

The relationship between DataStorage and Patient, and between Patient and PatientRecord, is composition. I used composition because patients belong to the storage, and records belong to the patient. If a patient is removed, their records should also be removed, so this shows strong ownership.

The AlertGenerator has a dependency to Patient and Alert. This is because it uses these classes in its methods but does not store them directly. It checks patient data and creates alerts when needed.

The ThresholdRule class is connected to both Patient and AlertGenerator. Each patient can have multiple rules, so I used a one-to-many relationship. The generator uses these rules to decide if a value is outside the normal range.

Finally, AlertManager is connected to Alert with a simple association. It manages and sends multiple alerts, so the multiplicity is 0..*. I separated this from AlertGenerator so that creating alerts and sending them are different responsibilities.

